'''Nagu Shrine''' (奈具神社) is a {{ill|Shinto shrine|ja|神社|12=draft}} located in Yura, {{ill|Miyazu, Kyoto|ja|宮津市|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kyoto Prefecture|ja|京都府|12=draft}}, Japan. It is an {{ill|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|ja|式内社|1=Shikinaisha|12=draft}} and one of the eleven shrines of {{ill|Kasa District, Tango Province|ja|加佐郡|12=draft}}.

== deity ==
The enshrined deity is {{ill|Toyouke-Ōmikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|12=draft}}, also known as {{ill|Toyouke-bime|ja|豊宇賀能賣命|12=draft}}, who is identified with the celestial maiden ({{ill|Tennyo|ja|天女|12=draft}}) from the {{ill|Hagoromo legend|ja|羽衣伝承|12=draft}}.

* {{ill|Toyouke-bime|ja|豊宇賀能賣命|12=draft}}

== Annual Festivals ==
* {{ill|Kinensai|ja|祈年祭|12=draft}} - April 10
* {{ill|Reisai|ja|festival|12=draft}} - October 10
* {{ill|Niinamesai|ja|新嘗祭|12=draft}} - November 23

== History ==
There is another shrine with the same name, Nagu Shrine, located in {{ill|Funaki, Yasaka, Kyotango|ja|弥栄町|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kyotango, Kyoto|ja|京丹後市|12=draft}}. This shrine is also a Shikinai-sha and one of the fourteen shrines of {{ill|Takeno District, Tango Province|ja|竹野郡 (京都府)|12=draft}}.

According to the {{ill|Tango Fudoki|ja|丹後国風土記|12=draft}}, the name "Nagu" derives from the word "Nagusiku" (meaning "to be at peace"), referring to the peaceful heart of the deity.

{{quotation|
<poem>
Long ago, a celestial maiden descended to the sacred well of Hiji in the district of {{ill|Tanba Province|ja|丹波の郡|12=draft}}. She was persuaded by an elderly couple, Wanana and Sana, to remain in the village of Hiji, where she brewed sake believed to cure all ailments, bringing great wealth to the couple. However, the couple, driven by greed, eventually cast her out, declaring, "You are not our child."

She composed the following poem:
''"Looking up at the vast heavens, shrouded in mist, I have lost my way and do not know my path."''

After leaving Hiji, she wandered through many villages until she arrived at the village of Nagu in Funaki. There she declared, ''"Here, my heart has found peace (nagusiku),"'' and decided to settle. After her passing, the villagers enshrined her as {{ill|Toyouke-bime|ja|豊宇賀能賣命|12=draft}}. This is the origin of Nagu Shrine in Takeno District.
</poem>|From the shrine grounds information board: "About the deity of the {{ill|Shikinai-sha|ja|延喜式内|12=draft}} Nagu Shrine"}}

== Access ==
* Approximately 900 meters northwest of {{ill|Tango-Yura Station|ja|丹後由良駅|12=draft}} on the {{ill|Miyamai Line|ja|京都丹後鉄道宮舞線|12=draft}}, {{ill|Kyoto Tango Railway|ja|京都丹後鉄道|12=draft}}.

